04375nam a22005655i 9780228014980DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280149807 a10.1515/97802280149802doi  a(DE-B1597)655393  a(OCoLC)1322990976  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aHIS0060102bisacsh04a133.4/260971409032qOCoLC223/eng/202311201 aCowan, Mairi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Possession of Barbe Hallay :bDiabolical Arts and Daily Life in Early Canada /cMairi Cowan. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource :b11 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Early Canada / Avant le Canada00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tAcross the Atlantic -- tThe Servant, the Miller, and the Infested Seigneurie -- tMissionary Demonologists -- tA Deliverance from Demons -- tTo the Other Shore -- tConclusion -- tGlossary -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen strange signs appeared in the sky over Québec during the autumn of 1660, people began to worry about evil forces in their midst. They feared that witches and magicians had arrived in the colony, and a teenaged servant named Barbe Hallay started to act as if she were possessed. The community tried to make sense of what was happening, and why. Priests and nuns performed rituals to drive the demons away, while the bishop and the governor argued about how to investigate their suspicions of witchcraft. A local miller named Daniel Vuil, accused of using his knowledge of the dark arts to torment Hallay, was imprisoned and then executed.Stories of the demonic infestation circulated through the small settlement on the St Lawrence River for several years. In The Possession of Barbe Hallay Mairi Cowan revisits these stories to understand the everyday experiences and deep anxieties of people in New France. Her findings offer insight into beliefs about demonology and witchcraft, the limits of acceptable adolescent behaviour, the dissonance between a Catholic colony in theory and the church’s wavering influence in practice, the contested authority accorded to women as healers, and the insecurities of the colonial project. As the people living through the events knew at the time, and as this study reveals, New France was in a precarious position.The Possession of Barbe Hallay is both a fascinating account of a case of demonic possession and an accessible introduction to social and religious history in early modern North America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanada-History-To 1763 (New-France). 0aDemoniac possessionzQuébec (Province)xHistoryy17th century. 0aDemoniac possession. 0aHallay, Barbe. 0aWitchcraftzQuébec (Province)xHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Pre-Confederation (to 1867).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022z978311127419540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228014980?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228014980423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228014980/original  a978-3-11-127214-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-127419-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles